BSE in Japan - fourth case (OIE Emergency Report)
-------------------------------------------------
Dr Toshikazu Ijichi, director of Animal Health Division, Ministry of
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, Tokyo, reported on 13 May 2002 that a
Holstein cow aged 6 years and one month kept on a dairy farm in Shiranuka
Gun, Hokkaido Prefecture was slaughtered at the abattoir on 10 May 2002.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species / susceptible / cases / deaths / destroyed / slaughtered
bov / 56 / 1 / 0 / 0 / 1
The brain sample from the cow tested positive to the enzyme linked
immunosorbent assay based bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) screening
test required by the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare for all cattle
slaughtered at abattoirs since 18 Oct 2001. The test was carried out at
Hokkaido Prefectural Kushiro Public Health Center, Kushiro City, Hokkaido
Prefecture.
The brain sample was sent to the Obihiro University of Agriculture and
Veterinary Medicine,Obihiro City, Hokkaido Prefecture for confirmation,
where western blot analysis and immunohistochemical examination yielded a
positive result on 12 May 2002.
The source of agent/origin of infection are under investigation.
Control measures are as follows. The dairy farm in Hokkaido Prefecture
where the BSE case was found has been placed under movement control by the
Kushiroe Livestock Hygiene Service Centre. All animals that were kept with
the infected cow [are being/have been] identified. The feed used on the
farm, as a possible source of infection, is being subjected to
epidemiological investigation.
Note from the OIE Central Bureau: This is the fourth BSE case reported in
Japan. As from now, any further cases of BSE in Japan will no longer be
notified in Disease Information but will immediately be incorporated into
the table on the number of reported cases of BSE worldwide (excluding the
United Kingdom), which can be consulted on the OIE website
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/en_esbmonde.htm>.
[Japan's official report on its first BSE case, sent on 10 Sep 2001,
indicated that the nature of the diagnosis was "clinical and laboratory";
in their initial, preliminary report of 10 Sept 2001, and mentioned
dystaxia of the suspected cow. In all 3 subsequent cases (reported to OIE
on 22 Nov 2002, 05 Dec 2002, and 13 May 2002) the nature of diagnosis was
indicated as "laboratory". However, the Japanese daily Asahi Shimbun,
reporting on the fourth case on 13 May 2002, said that "veterinarians, on
Thu (09 May 2002), diagnosed the cow with a suspected case of neural
paralysis in the left front leg".
<http://www.asahi.com/english/national/K2002051300397.html>.
We hope the Japanese authorities will be able to shed more light on the
clinical aspects of the last 3 cases. - Mod.AS].
