Date: 25 May 2002
From:ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Danish Veterinary and Food Administration- press release, 15 May
2002 [translated from Danish and abridged by Dr Hanna Adler, edited].
<http://www.vfd.dk/vtnyt/frameset_bse.html>

New case of mad cow disease, Denmark
------------------------------------
The 8th case of BSE has been detected in Denmark. The cow, a 5 years and 6
months old red Dane dairy cow from an organic farm on the Baltic island of
Bornholm, was slaughtered on 25 Apr 2002. The case was discovered by
routine testing at slaughter. The sampled brain tissue tested positive at
Steins Laboratory and was forwarded to the National Veterinary Institute in
Copenhagen for confirmation. The cow was born and lived its entire life on
the same dairy farm of 127 milkers and 127 calves.
Following the final confirmation of the diagnosis, all animals on the farm
were destroyed, as well as 46 other animals that had been sold to 12 farms
in Denmark. In addition, all bovines older then 24 months on these 12 farms
are to be checked for BSE [at slaughter?].
The positive slaughtered cow was destroyed together with 3 other cows at
the slaughterhouse -- one which was slaughtered immediately before her and
2 cows slaughtered after her.
The feed source on the affected farm is being investigated; the results
will be published. It has been found that no animal originating in the
affected farm has been exported.
