Date: 25 May 2002
From:ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Warsaw Voice, No 19 (707), 12 May 2002 [edited]
<http://www.warsawvoice.pl/v707/Business02.html>

BSE in Poland
-------------
Poland's first case of a cow infected with bovine spongiform encephalitis
(BSE) has been detected in a slaughterhouse near Krynica, Malopolska
province. The European Union will not introduce new restrictions on the
importation of Polish beef, but exports to central and eastern Europe may
become a problem, as all the Baltic states banned imports of Polish cattle,
beef, and meat products based on beef early last week.
The start of the year promised to bring a watershed in the beef market.
Unexpectedly, Polish meat exports to the former Soviet Union increased and
demand for beef also increased at home. Producers managed to win consumers'
confidence that Poland was a country free from BSE. The consequences of
discovering the first case of the disease may mean a big headache for
producers.
Many experts say the case does not alter the fact that Poland is a low risk
country for the occurrence of the disease. The EU has confirmed this
opinion. The European Commission has offered assurances that it will not
introduce new restrictions on imports of Polish beef. "The EU does not have
to be afraid of imports from Poland, because there have been strict
controls of imported meat for a long time," said Beate Gminder,
spokesperson for the EU commissioner for consumer protection.
The EU has classified Poland among "high risk BSE" countries -- category 3
on a scale of 1 to 4 [seems to contradict previous paragraph. - Mod.SH].
Only about 20 meat plants in Poland, out of 3500, have the right to export
beef to the 15 member states. They buy cattle from breeders who offer
guarantees that the animals were not fed animal-derived feed and did not
die in suspicious circumstances. Other meat plants which produce either for
the domestic market or for export to countries other than EU member states
do not offer such guarantees.
Veterinary surgeon general Piotr Kolodziejczyk said the detection of the
disease would make the Polish supervision system over the slaughter of
cattle and the safety of Polish beef more reliable in the eyes of the EU.
Still, in his opinion, the situation for producers may deteriorate due to
the lost confidence among domestic consumers. "Painting bleak scenarios may
unnecessarily provoke panic among consumers," Kolodziejczyk said. "We
already know its scope and implications from western Europe."
Beef exports to central and eastern European countries are also threatened.
Przemyslaw Chabowski, head of the Polish Union of Meat Producers, Exporters
and Importers, said that the occurrence of further outbreaks of BSE is an
unrealistic threat. But one should not forget that western cattle were
imported to Poland in the 1990s that may have been infected, he cautioned.
"If there are more outbreaks of the disease, we may witness another crisis
in the beef market," said Chabowski. "It remains unknown how foreign buyers
will behave. The situation may especially alarm companies that made
painstaking efforts to sign contracts with Ukraine and Russia."
The first repercussions caused by BSE in Poland have come from Lithuania.
The Lithuanian state service for food control and veterinary science
introduced a ban on imports of Polish beef on 6 May 2002. The head of the
Lithuanian veterinary services said a meat plant in Vilnius has imported 88
tons of beef from Poland this year, but the beef was tested and had a
safety certificate. Representatives of Polish exporters say the decision of
the Lithuanian services was political, and the BSE case in Poland was only
an excuse to introduce a ban on imports of Polish beef. Latvia, Estonia,
and Ukraine followed suit, and have banned Polish beef imports since 7 May
2002.
Poland's credibility will certainly not be helped by the fact that it is
still not known where exactly the infected cow came from. It has transpired
that the trader who supplied the cow to the slaughterhouse produced false
documents of the animal's origin.
[Byline: R.S.]
