Date: 25 May 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PAP news agency, Warsaw, in English, via BBC Monitoring
International Reports, 15 May 2002 [edited]

Polish BSE cow's mother herd located
------------------------------------
Cracow: Poland's first known BSE -infected cow originally came from a herd
in Rzepiennik Strzyzewski, southern Poland, genetic experts concluded (on)
Wed, 15 May 2002.
Local officials have said that 2 other animals in the same herd known to be
related to the sick cow have also been found. All 3 animals will be put to
sleep, after which their brains will be vivisected.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Additional data on the evolving BSE situation and related steps in Poland
have been compiled from several Polish electronic sources, mainly "Zrodlo:
Internet z dnia", 5-10 May 2002. We are very grateful to Mr Shlomo Dori for
his translations.
1. The Polish police arrested 2 people in connection with the illegal
transfer of the infected cow (a dealer and an official) accused of
documents forgery.
2. The 9 year old animal was suspected for BSE within the mass screening
testing scheme; it did not manifest clinical symptoms. The cow arrived at
the slaughterhouse with other animals probably -- but not certainly --
coming from the same farm. The fact that the cow did not carry
identification (such as ear tags) caused a long delay in the tracing of the
farm. For these investigations, genetic techniques have been applied. The
police argued that if the cow had been properly identifiable, the
investigation could be completed within minutes instead of more than 48 hours.
3. The owner insisted that he had never used meat and bone meal on his
farm. [Even if this is found to be true, it does not exclude the use of
milk-replacers].
4. The case underlined the worrisome lack of official and general
identification of cattle in Poland. A steering committee headed by the
deputy minister of agriculture has been established and is engaged in the
planning and coordination of the nationwide identification of Polish
cattle. This will include the ear tagging of each head in the national herd
with 2 ear tags, accompanied by an individual identity card. The project is
planned to become operational on 1 Sep 2002, with a budget of 20 million
Euros secured by the government. Specific new legislation will be required.
The services of an internationally recognized computer company have been
sought.
5. The authorities are to launch a campaign against illegal ("gray")
slaughter outside the slaughterhouses. - Mod.AS]
